def countplot(cols):
    # Print value counts
    print(df[cols].value_counts(normalize=True) * 100)

    # Set figure size
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))  # You can adjust these dimensions as needed
    
    # Create countplot
    ax = sns.countplot(x=cols, data=df)
    
    # Get total number of data points in the column
    total = len(df[cols])
    
    # Annotate percentage values on the plot
    for p in ax.patches:
        label = "{:.1f}%".format(100 * p.get_height() / total)
        
        # Position the text on the bar
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2
        y = p.get_height()
        
        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=10,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points"
        )
    # Show plot
    plt.show()

def bivariate(cols):

    ax=sns.countplot(x=cols,hue='case_status',data=df)
    total=len(df[cols])
    for p in ax.patches:
        label="{:.1f}%".format(100*p.get_height()/total)

        x=p.get_x()+p.get_width()/2
        y=p.get_height()

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x,y),
            size=10,
            ha='center',
            va='center',
            xytext=(0,5),
            textcoords="offset points"
        )
    plt.show()

Model Evaluation criterion

In [42]:
#function to evaluate metrics
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score,recall_score,precision_score,f1_score
def metrics_evaluation(model,predictors,target):
    #predicting values of  data
    y_pred=model.predict(predictors)
    #metrics evaluation
    f1=f1_score(target,y_pred)
    recall=recall_score(target,y_pred)
    precision=precision_score(target,y_pred)
    accuracy=accuracy_score(target,y_pred)
    
    perf=pd.DataFrame({
        'Accuracy':accuracy,
        'Precision':precision,
        'Recall': recall,
        'f1_score':f1},index=[0])
    return perf
In [43]:
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
#function for confusion matrix
def confusion_mat(model,predictors,target):
    #predicting values of data
    y_pred=model.predict(predictors)

    #confusion matrix
    cm=confusion_matrix(target,y_pred)

    labels=np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2,2)
    plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
    sns.heatmap(cm,annot=labels,fmt="")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted values")
    plt.ylabel("True values")
    plt.show()

Decision Tree model with HyperParameter Tuning

In [49]:
#hyper parameter tunin using GridSearchCV
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.metrics import make_scorer

dt_gs=DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42,class_weight='balanced')

parameters = {
    "max_depth": np.arange(10, 30, 5),
    "min_samples_leaf": [3, 5, 7],
    "max_leaf_nodes": [2, 3, 5],
    "min_impurity_decrease": [0.0001, 0.001],
}
# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
f1_scorer=make_scorer(f1_score)

grid_dt=GridSearchCV(dt_gs,parameters,scoring=f1_scorer,cv=5)

#fit the model
grid_dt.fit(X_train,y_train)

print("best parameters are",grid_dt.best_params_)

#fitting the data to best-estimator
dt_gs=grid_dt.best_estimator_
dt_gs.fit(X_train,y_train)

best parameters are {'max_depth': np.int64(10), 'max_leaf_nodes': 2, 'min_impurity_decrease': 0.0001, 'min_samples_leaf': 3}

    "max_samples": [0.7, 0.8, 0.9],

    "n_estimators": np.arange(90, 120, 10)
}

#f1_score=make_scorer(f1_score)
